&quot;Holliday, Donald B. (LNG-SHEP)&quot; wrote:

&gt; &lt;snip&gt;Using a debugger should be the last thing you do to debug a module.
&gt; It takes a lot of time.&lt;/snip
&gt;
&gt; Interesting attitude.
&gt;
&gt; In Code Complete Steve McConnell states &quot;Once a routine compiles, put it
&gt; into the debugger and step through each line of code.  Make sure each line
&gt; executes as you expect it to.  You can find many errors by following this
&gt; simple practice.&quot;

I don&#39;t think Steve McConnell is right here, but of course that&#39;s just my
opinion.

&gt;
&gt;
&gt; I find his advice useful.  It is especially helpful in a debugger like VAJ
&gt; as you can easily force code into error traps that are almost impossible to
&gt; induce during testing (like a database going down during a query, or the
&gt; network failing after you wrote to a socket, or a remote host failing after
&gt; you connected).
&gt;

Sounds like a useful feature in the debugger.  However, without having
repeatable jUnit tests, you&#39;ll not be getting maximum productivity over the life
of the system.  Having to use a debugger each time you make modifications,
instead of having a test suite that tests things like a database going down, or
a network going down.

&gt;
&gt; Donald Holliday
&gt;
