&gt;
&gt; For the sake of discussing software engineering, I&#39;d like to point out that
&gt; it
&gt; is often less productive to use a debugger. Consider that using
&gt; org.log4j.Category as a class var in your program, then: (assuming you have
&gt; a
&gt; Debug class with a booleans SHALLOW, MEDIUM, DEEP )
&gt;
&gt; if( Debug.SHALLOW )
&gt;     Log_.debug( &quot;got to just after xxx, someVar=&quot;+someVar )
&gt;
&gt; Here is a sample out put using Log_.info(..) in a debug run (actually a
&gt; jUnit
&gt; test case.)
&gt;
&gt; 0 [main] INFO com.popetools.util.Debug  -
&gt; util.debug.static.OpenAppender(..):
&gt; log opened successfully.
&gt; .370 [main] INFO com.popetools.unittest.PersistenceManagerExceptionTest  -
&gt; testCurrTransWhileClosed passed.
&gt;
&gt; The first field indicates the millis that elapsed since the start of
&gt; execution, and the 3rd field indicates the class emitting the output, and
&gt; the
&gt; rest of the line is the emitted information.
&gt;
&gt; After you&#39;ve debugged the code, you replace the SHALLOW with MEDIUM, or DEEP
&gt; considering on the level of detail output it produces.
&gt;
&gt; This way, the poor sod who makes a change to your code later, and needs to
&gt; debug it, already has the important debug state-check points indicated.
&gt; He/she simply has to replace the MEDIUM with SHALLOW, turn on Debug.SHALLOW,
&gt; and presto, they can debug your code with minimal effort.
&gt;
&gt; In the long haul, such schemes save time and effort.  Using a debugger
&gt; should
&gt; be the last thing you do to debug a module.  It takes a lot of time.
&gt;
&gt; Regards,
&gt; Matthew
